00:14:15.810 --> 00:14:19.790
expected value calculation
is the same thing as the

00:14:19.790 --> 00:14:23.670
population mean calculation,
but we do it this way because

00:14:23.670 --> 00:14:27.360
you can't add up an infinite
number of data points and

00:14:27.360 --> 00:14:28.650
divide by an infinite number.

00:14:28.650 --> 00:14:30.880
Instead you want to know the
frequencies of each of the

00:14:30.880 --> 00:14:34.500
outcomes and then you just add
up all the outcomes weighted

00:14:34.500 --> 00:14:35.450
by their frequencies.

00:14:35.450 --> 00:14:37.290
But that's no different than
what you did up there.

00:14:37.290 --> 00:14:39.000
And I really want to hit that
point home because sometimes in

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:41.160
probability books they'll just
give you a formula-- oh, the

00:14:41.160 --> 00:14:43.590
expected value of a probability
distribution is each of the

00:14:43.590 --> 00:14:45.330
outcomes times their frequency.

00:14:45.330 --> 00:14:47.960
But I want to show you that
that is the same thing

00:14:47.960 --> 00:14:49.470
as the population mean.

00:14:49.470 --> 00:14:51.900
